    <!-- Learn -->
    <string name="learn_title">Learn</string>
    <string name="learn_intro">Short, practical cards from the coffee knowledge base.</string>
    <string name="learn_read_more">Read</string>
    <string name="learn_troubleshoot_title">How was your cup?</string>
    <string name="learn_troubleshoot_intro">Tell me how it tasted and I\'ll suggest a tweak for next time.</string>
    <string name="taste_sour">Sour</string>
    <string name="taste_bitter">Bitter</string>
    <string name="taste_weak">Weak / hollow</string>
    <string name="taste_strong">Too strong</string>
    <string name="taste_balanced">Balanced</string>
    <string name="taste_sour_advice">Under-extracted. Grind a touch finer, raise the water temperature 2–3°C, or extend the brew time.</string>
    <string name="taste_bitter_advice">Over-extracted. Grind a touch coarser, drop the water temperature 2–3°C, or shorten the brew time.</string>
    <string name="taste_weak_advice">Strengthen the ratio (more coffee or less water) and increase agitation. Check that your beans are fresh.</string>
    <string name="taste_strong_advice">Dilute the ratio — add more water or use slightly less coffee next time.</string>
    <string name="taste_balanced_advice">Nailed it. Save this recipe so you can repeat it exactly.</string>

    <!-- Learn card titles -->
    <string name="learn_c1_title">The Golden Cup</string>
    <string name="learn_c1_body">Only ~28–30%% of a coffee bean is soluble. A great brew extracts 18–22%% of those solids at a strength (TDS) of 1.15–1.45%%. Below the window coffee tastes sour and thin; above it, bitter and astringent.</string>
    <string name="learn_c2_title">Grind is king</string>
    <string name="learn_c2_body">Particle size decides extraction. Burr grinders keep ~75–85%% of grounds at the target size; blade grinders scatter fines and boulders, giving you sourness and bitterness in the same cup. Grind right before brewing — ground coffee goes stale within 15 minutes.</string>
    <string name="learn_c3_title">Water is 98%% of your cup</string>
    <string name="learn_c3_body">Aim for ~150 ppm TDS (SCA: 75–250), general hardness 50–175 ppm and alkalinity 40–70 ppm. Chlorine ruins delicate aromatics — a simple carbon filter is the cheapest upgrade you can make.</string>
    <string name="learn_c4_title">Water temperature</string>
    <string name="learn_c4_body">90–96°C suits most methods. Rest boiling water 30–60 seconds first. Light roasts like the lower end to protect delicate aromatics; a cooler pour (≈88°C) can tame a dark roast\'s bitterness.</string>
    <string name="learn_c5_title">Bloom</string>
    <string name="learn_c5_body">Fresh coffee holds CO₂ that repels water and causes uneven extraction. Pour 2–4× the coffee weight in water and wait 30–45 seconds. The bed swells and bubbles — that\'s the gas escaping. Crucial for pour-over, minor for immersion.</string>
    <string name="learn_c6_title">Roast &amp; freshness</string>
    <string name="learn_c6_body">Coffee peaks 5–14 days after roasting. Rest filter coffee 7–10 days, espresso 14–21. Store beans airtight, opaque and cool. Oxygen, light, heat and moisture are the four enemies.</string>
    <string name="learn_c7_title">Reading your cup</string>
    <string name="learn_c7_body">Sour &amp; sharp → under-extracted: grind finer, hotter, longer. Bitter &amp; dry → over-extracted: grind coarser, cooler, shorter. Flat &amp; hollow → strengthen the ratio and stir more.</string>
    <string name="learn_c8_title">Bean species</string>
    <string name="learn_c8_body">Arabica (60–70%% of production) is sweeter and more acidic with ~1.2%% caffeine. Robusta (30–40%%) is bolder, more bitter, ~2.4%% caffeine, and builds crema in espresso blends.</string>
    <string name="learn_c9_title">Processing</string>
    <string name="learn_c9_body">Washed = clean and bright, origin-forward. Natural = fruity, wine-like, heavy body. Honey = syrupy sweetness in between. Anaerobic = intense, exotic, experimental.</string>
    <string name="learn_c10_title">Tools that matter</string>
    <string name="learn_c10_body">A good burr grinder is the single best investment. A 0.1 g scale + timer make every brew repeatable. A gooseneck kettle gives 2–5 g/s pour control for even pour-over beds.</string>
